Encoding "Galaxy" column in both datasets¶

there is only one column which consists of strings: Galaxy. We have to change this column into numeric. Tehrefore, we will use One Hot Encoding method

In [84]:
encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False)
encoded_galaxy = encoder.fit_transform(df_train[['galaxy']])
encoded_df = pd.DataFrame(encoded_galaxy, columns=encoder.get_feature_names_out(['galaxy']))
df_train = pd.concat([df_train, encoded_df], axis=1)
df_train = df_train.drop('galaxy', axis=1)
In [85]:
y_column = df_train['y']
df_train = df_train.drop(columns=['y'])
df_train['y'] = y_column
In [86]:
test_encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False)
test_encoded_galaxy = encoder.fit_transform(df_test[['galaxy']])
test_encoded_df = pd.DataFrame(test_encoded_galaxy, columns=encoder.get_feature_names_out(['galaxy']))
df_test = pd.concat([df_test, test_encoded_df], axis=1)
df_test = df_test.drop('galaxy', axis=1)

As we see, after encoding "Galaxy" column, the total number of columns in Train dataset is 10 columns more than the total number of columns in Train dataset. This is becasue, there are some galaxies which are present in Train dataset but are not present in Test dataset. Therefore, I will delete these extra 9 columns.¶
